snippet.textDisplay:
Something to note is that Steve is the only entity able to respawn in the game. Sure mobs spawn and you can respawn the ender dragon as well as other mobs, but he is the only one that is the same entity as it was before it died. All of the other mobs get different data and are completely new, while Steve retains his spawn location, achievements, stats, and other entity-specific data. This could explain the Illager's interest in him, given their apparent theme of life and death. An alternate theory that I have seen circulating in the comments is the idea that Steve was created by the Illagers, hence him being the only unique mob in the game. This means they would've succeeded, but not in the way they had hoped as it now fights against them. They are now trying to make their next "version" be obedient, which explains the remaining wool and altars. But that's just a theory, a comment theory.


Edit: I just realized that the evokers area also the only mobs who summon other mobs to fight for them in the game. However, they eventually suffocate in the air and cannot sustain themselves which is why they are only used for combat. This only goes to show their interest in life and death more.

snippet.textDisplay: Story time from me: I was playing Minecraft in survival, I was in mountains by the sea. One day I’m looking around for adventure and I see a structure in the distance, still on a mountain. Across the mountain I’m standing on there was a very tall sand dune. On top of it I saw a little structure, I immediately ran over there. It was an underwater structure on land, it had a chest and everything with things you’d find in the sea. There were two or more of the structures, I can’t remember. I assume that’s proving that erosion can happen in Minecraft or its just a glitch, you never know when it comes to Minecraft. Maybe I’m wasting your time, maybe I’m right. Who knows?
